  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mt-10 mb-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What does a three-phase decanter centrifuge separate?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">A three-phase decanter centrifuge simultaneously separates solids and two immiscible liquid phases — typically oil, water, and solids — in a single pass. Common applications include olive oil processing, fish oil extraction, slop oil recovery, produced water treatment, and biodiesel glycerin separation.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">When should I use a three-phase decanter instead of a two-phase decanter plus a disc centrifuge?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Choose a three-phase decanter when feed solids content is high (typically above 3% by volume), a combined footprint or cost advantage is important, and both solids discharge and two-liquid separation are required simultaneously. For very low-solids feeds where liquid-liquid separation quality is paramount, a two-phase decanter followed by a <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-faq/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">disc centrifuge</a> may deliver better final liquid clarity.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">How is pond depth adjusted on a three-phase decanter?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Pond depth on a three-phase decanter is set by adjusting the weir radius for both the heavy and light liquid phases. Three requirements must be balanced simultaneously: liquid residence time for oil-water stratification, solids conveying performance, and weir overflow ratios. This makes three-phase pond depth adjustment more complex than on a standard two-phase decanter.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

